			</div><div id="intent-accordion" class="md-intent-accordion"><div class="top-question bg-gray-50 rounded" data-value="1"> <h3 class="accordion--question font-14 font-weight-normal cursor-pointer rounded"><div class="pe-none d-flex justify-content-between align-items-center"><div> What is St. Albertus Magnus the patron&nbsp;saint&nbsp;of? </div><em class="material-icons" data-icon="expand_more"></em></div></h3> <div class="accordion--answer hidden p-15 pt-5 font-16 mb-5"><div class="accordion--answer-copy"><p>St. Albertus Magnus was declared the <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/patron-saint" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">patron saint</a> of natural sciences in 1941.</p></div></div> </div><div class="top-question bg-gray-50 rounded" data-value="2"> <h3 class="accordion--question font-14 font-weight-normal cursor-pointer rounded"><div class="pe-none d-flex justify-content-between align-items-center"><div> What was St. Albertus Magnusâ€™s contribution to science? </div><em class="material-icons" data-icon="expand_more"></em></div></h3> <div class="accordion--answer hidden p-15 pt-5 font-16 mb-5"><div class="accordion--answer-copy"><p>St. Albertus Magnus established the study of nature as a legitimate <a href="https://www.britannica.com/science/science" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">science</a> within the <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/Christianity" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Christian</a> tradition and made <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/Aristotelianism" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Aristotelian</a> knowledge of nature accessible, enriching it with his own observations.</p></div></div> </div><div class="top-question bg-gray-50 rounded" data-value="3"> <h3 class="accordion--question font-14 font-weight-normal cursor-pointer rounded"><div class="pe-none d-flex justify-content-between align-items-center"><div> What role did St. Albertus Magnus play at the University of Paris? </div><em class="material-icons" data-icon="expand_more"></em></div></h3> <div class="accordion--answer hidden p-15 pt-5 font-16 mb-5"><div class="accordion--answer-copy"><p>St. Albertus Magnus lectured on the <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/Bible" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Bible</a> and <a href="https://www.britannica.com/biography/Peter-Lombard" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Peter Lombard</a>â€™s <em>Sentences</em> at the University of Paris, and he worked on a comprehensive presentation of knowledge, including commentaries on <a href="https://www.britannica.com/biography/Aristotle" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Aristotle</a>â€™s works.</p></div></div> </div><div class="top-question bg-gray-50 rounded" data-value="4"> <h3 class="accordion--question font-14 font-weight-normal cursor-pointer rounded"><div class="pe-none d-flex justify-content-between align-items-center"><div> What was St. Albertus Magnusâ€™s relationship with Thomas Aquinas? </div><em class="material-icons" data-icon="expand_more"></em></div></h3> <div class="accordion--answer hidden p-15 pt-5 font-16 mb-5"><div class="accordion--answer-copy"><p>St. Albertus Magnus was a teacher and mentor to <a href="https://www.britannica.com/biography/Saint-Thomas-Aquinas" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Thomas Aquinas</a>, maintaining a close relationship despite some doctrinal differences. Aquinas was one of his chief disciples. Several years after Aquinasâ€™s death in 1274, Albertus traveled to <a href="https://www.britannica.com/place/Paris" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Paris</a> to uphold the recently condemned good name and writings of his former student.</p></div></div> </div><button class="show-more-button js-toggle-top-questions btn btn-unstyled font-14 d-flex pr-10 rounded-sm" aria-label="Show more questions"><em class="material-icons" data-icon="expand_more"></em></button></div></div><!--[BEFORE-ARTICLE]--><span class="marker before-article"></span><section data-level="1" id="ref1"><!--[PREMOD1]--><span class="marker PREMOD1 mod-inline"></span><p class="topic-paragraph"><strong><span id="ref189208"></span>St. Albertus Magnus</strong> (born c. 1200, Lauingen an der Donau, <a href="https://www.britannica.com/place/Swabia" class="md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-preview="true">Swabia</a> [Germany]â€”died November 15, 1280, Cologne; canonized December 16, 1931; feast day November 15) was a <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/Dominican-order" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Dominican</a> bishop and philosopher best known as a teacher of <a href="https://www.britannica.com/biography/Saint-Thomas-Aquinas" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">St. Thomas Aquinas</a> and as a proponent of <span id="ref189209"></span><a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/Aristotelianism" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Aristotelianism</a> at the <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/Universities-of-Paris-I-XIII" class="md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-preview="true">University of Paris</a>. He established the study of nature as a <a class="md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term="legitimate" href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/legitimate" data-type="MW">legitimate</a> <a href="https://www.britannica.com/science/science" class="md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-preview="true">science</a> within the <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/Christianity" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Christian</a> tradition. He was the most <a class="md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term="prolific" href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/prolific" data-type="MW">prolific</a> writer of his century and was the only scholar of his age to be called â€œthe Greatâ€; this title was used even before his death. In 1931 Pope <a href="https://www.britannica.com/biography/Pius-XI" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Pius XI</a> made Albertus a <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/Doctor-of-the-Church" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">doctor of the church</a>, a title given to <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/Roman-Catholicism" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Roman Catholic</a> <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/saint" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">saints</a> whose writings have special authority. By papal decree in 1941, he was declared the <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/patron-saint" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">patron saint</a> of all who <a class="md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term="cultivate" href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/cultivate" data-type="MW">cultivate</a> the natural sciences.</p><!--[MOD1]--><span class="marker MOD1 mod-inline"></span></section>              <!--[H2]--><span class="marker h2"></span><section data-level="1" id="ref454156"> <h2 class="h1">Education</h2> <!--[PREMOD2]--><span class="marker PREMOD2 mod-inline"></span><p class="topic-paragraph">Albertus was the eldest son of a wealthy German lord. After his early schooling, he went to the <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/University-of-Padua" class="md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-preview="true">University of Padua</a>, where he studied the <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/liberal-arts" class="md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-preview="true">liberal arts</a>. He joined the <span id="ref189210"></span><a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/Dominican-order" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Dominican</a> order at <a href="https://www.britannica.com/place/Padua-Italy" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Padua</a> in 1223. He continued his studies at Padua and <a href="https://www.britannica.com/place/Bologna-Italy" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Bologna</a> and in <a href="https://www.britannica.com/place/Germany" class="md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-preview="true">Germany</a> and then taught <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/theology" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">theology</a> at several convents throughout Germany, lastly at <a href="https://www.britannica.com/place/Cologne-Germany" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Cologne</a>.</p><!--[MOD2]--><span class="marker MOD2 mod-inline"></span> <!--[PREMOD3]--><span class="marker PREMOD3 mod-inline"></span><p class="topic-paragraph">Sometime before 1245 he was sent to the Dominican <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/convent" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">convent</a> of Saint-Jacques at the University of Paris, where he came into contact with the works of <span id="ref189211"></span><a href="https://www.britannica.com/biography/Aristotle" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Aristotle</a>, newly translated from Greek and Arabic, and with the commentaries on Aristotleâ€™s works by <a href="https://www.britannica.com/biography/Averroes" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">AverroÃ«s</a>, a 12th-century Spanish-Arabian philosopher. At Saint-Jacques he lectured on the <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/Bible" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Bible</a> for two years and then for another two years on <a href="https://www.britannica.com/biography/Peter-Lombard" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Peter Lombard</a>â€™s <em><span id="ref189212"></span><a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/Four-Books-of-Sentences" class="md-crosslink ">Sentences</a></em>, the theological textbook of the <a class="md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term="medieval" href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/medieval" data-type="MW">medieval</a> universities. In 1245 he was graduated master in the theological faculty and obtained the Dominican chair â€œfor foreigners.â€</p><a class="link-module shadow-sm d-block qa-quiz-module" href="/quiz/christianity-quiz">
	
	




































    
    
    
